ish himself as an improbable, yet inevitable, leader of a mass movement. His support came from people whose economic interests were directly threatened by increases in the global scope of the U.S. economy, and—like other third party candidates of the twentieth century—from those without formal religious affiliations. Comparisons of the 1992 and 1996 campaigns show that the decline in support for Perot was, for the most part, uniform across geographic regions and demographic groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPresidential candidateszUnited States. 0aPresidential candidates. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectiony1992. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 0aThird parties (United States politics). 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aDjupe, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Christopher P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelen, Ted G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelen, Ted G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Timothy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Andrew D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer, Jeremy D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordin, Kenneth D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, David A. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmons, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmons, Solon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator